Content:
I have a question . 
I'm a student and soon I'm going on an internship and I'm going to work somewhere for a company that makes iiot solutions for companies but my question is what can I expect because I'm currently doing a program in college that has to do with iot but this has more to do with on electronics side, does anyone have any tips?(sorry for my bad english)

Author: brianpribe
Content: Prepare to learn and prepare to work. What I've noticed with internships is that you have to make the most you can from it. Most internships are very loosely defined, so you might get someone coffee, maybe do some testing for them, or something where you're doing your manager's menial tasks (not to say it's bad, but rather it's an in for seeing how a company is structured or what they are planning to do). Learn what you want to learn. Find out what you want to learn, by watching and listening.

Author: zwgrounded
Content: I feel like there should be a list of affordable devices and instruments created so new iiot solutions engineers can start investing in their own home PLC and electronics lab. For starters I'm thinking: multimeter, wire clippers, soldering gun, transistor set, capacitor set, relay push button set, small LCD screens, servo drivers and actuators, barometric pressure sensors, ultrasonic sensors, LEDs set, an arduino, a raspberry pi, a starter PLC, spare wires and cable, a label maker, and surely plenty more. I'm not sure what this would cost in total, but I progressively keep expanding my toolbox of gadgets and supplies for my home lab. Never stop learning @Deleted User, also know that collaboration wins over competition always - and its more fun.

Author: sherylmccrary
Content:
As Michael Rada was defining his version of  Industry 5.0 in Zack's interview last Tuesday, he talked about wasteful overproduction and how food disparities were about logistics, not shortage.  I sometimes volunteer for a local organization, Borderlands Produce Rescue. They bring unsold produce into  the cities from warehouses on the Arizona-Mexico border and distribute it to anybody wanting it. Otherwise all this goes to landfill !!! 

The prior weekend, they distributed 92,440 pounds of produce from 6 locations. And they do that every weekend.

Author: sherylmccrary
Content: These pics are from Saturday before we got working unloading pallets and packing 70-80 lb. boxes with some of everything for people to pick up. There was another 5 pallets of tomatoes, 6 or 7 of squash, peppers, melons.  This is EVERY week at a multiple sites. This has really opened my eyes about food distribution. With the price of diesel going up last week, they were afraid they'd have to cut back.

Author: marioishikawa
Content: Here is also a shame how much food is wasted, specially on transport. It is common to see dump trucks that should be carrying gravel being used for grains and leaking grains such as corn as if it were water rain falling from the truck to the road.

Author: hobbes1069
Content: While I was still living with me dad (I think it was during college) we replaced the fuse boxes with a modern circuit breaker panel. We ran romex to replace all the outlets. The only thing we didn't change was the lighting circuits. We left it on a separate fuse box because all of it was original knob-and-tube wiring in the attic. Of course since it was built in 1928 all the insulation was gone, so you had to be careful where you put your hands while in the attic. ğŸ˜…

Author: hobbes1069
Content: Never seen my dad sweat so much as when he was re-wiring the meter panel with the main hots.

Author: thedavidschultz
Content: Our house in Rockford was built in 1930 and still had nob & tube. The entire upstair was on one 15 A circuit, which made window A/C (house did not have central) a challenge. I spent a summer rewiring the entire house, only learning two light circuits original. Going from 16 circuits to 40 was a huge help (I used all but 2). I wanted to upgrade to 200A service, but this would have been a heavy lift.

Author: torije
Content:
For sure the EV sales is heavily affected by the incentives. The policy idea was to increase the number of EVs to a point where the supporting infrastructure would be good enough that it would make sense to buy one. Now that the goal is closer, you see a lot of the incentives go away or being reduced. In the beginning the most sold EV was the Nissan Leaf, because it was a really attractive offering as a secondary car. In the last few years, it's been the TM3 because it's a really attractive offering as a primary car. 

Would sales of new EVs outnumber gasoline ones without the subsidies? Absolutely not, but there is a very high probability that it will continue to do so when the last subsidy is removed. The prices have come down to a level that makes them competitive even if we added sales tax (which is the main subsidy right now) and most of the other subsidies are gone. 

Surveys in Norway have shown consistently over the last years that people who buy an EV value a lot of other stuff other than the subsidies. And a very common sentiment is that once someone has bought an EV, they are unwilling to go back to a ICE vehicle.

Author: torije
Content:
Not sure I understand what argument you are trying to make here. I don't think every vehicle class will move to batteries, but that's hardly an argument for keeping all vehicles powered by gasoline. There will likely always be some use for gasoline, and the army is likely to be a large portion of that, I also think it's highly unrealistic to have cross Atlantic flights on battery powered planes, but smaller 15-30 min flights with 10-30 passengers seems realistic on a 5-10 year timeline. 

The victory of EVs in Norway is the result of enforcing policies that make that attractive. It's a highly coordinated effort that turned out to work really well, and now we're getting the results from it, which is that most new vehicles are EVs and eventually that will be true of all cars, both new and old. 

Tesla having the most sold model in Norway over the last few years is probably mostly a result of them having a product that you can actually buy. The traditional car manufacturers have been slow to act, and struggling to deliver any kind of volume, meaning people wait months and months for delivery. Heck, Toyota is releasing their first EV this year, and Nissan spent years doing who know what after their success with the Leaf before finally shipping Ariya this year.

Content: A dream of the 1950's. I still think it would be cool, but I think cost to produce would not make it viable. I think Electric cars are the best option (at least so far.) I believe France is still working on Nuclear Fusion Technology I believe, and China may be as well.

Author: joshuastover
Content:
I understand the worry of Nuclear. It's an incredibly safe form of energy production, until it's not. When things go bad, they tend to go very bad (Chernobyl, Fukushima) and for other countries the threat of these still remains too recent (like 3 mile island here in the US.)

Overall, I think Nuclear is the best bet for safe, green, reliable, and low cost energy production. I think Solar is a great consumer option, and is much more effective if we used it on people's roofs, etc. The issue with Wind is maintenance cost. It's a great renewable energy, but so costly to maintain it tends to not be worth it to governments and companies to go out and repair them. Plus they have to bury the blades when they are at EOL because there is no cost-effective way to recycle them yet.

Author: benveenema
Content:
Heard.
Solar is the distributed, decentralized powerplant. What it lacks in efficiency, it makes up for resiliency and agility.
Nuclear (in any form) is the centralized power of the future. It is already safer than coal (https://ourworldindata.org/safest-sources-of-energy) but suffers from bad PR, high consequences and high targetability for attacks.

Wind is... Wind is just second order solar ğŸ¤£

Author: joshuastover
Content: Poor wind energy ğŸ¤£

Author: joshuastover
Content: What's unfortunate is that there are areas of the US (and presumably the rest of the world) that create negative incentives for people to be energy independent. I visited my mom last week and was talking to her about solar, and found out the city owned electrical company does not allow people to use energy produced by their own solar panels. Instead the solar energy goes back out to the grid and the city still charges for however much energy was used, regardless of how much was offset by a home solar system.

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
How does that work, if you connect the inverter inside the Meter the utility won't know what your using. There are reasons you need to follow the Code to ensure that your solar don't end up powering a line believed to be dead. SO I can't understand how they stop you using the power you produce.  Are they metering the inverter? 
Can you change the Electricity provider or are you tied to the utility in your locaity.

The incentives in Ireland are not too bad, though some still complain. No VAT( so a 23% saving there) There are also grants available. the utility don't know how much you produce they can only see your meter. so if you offset all your bill then no charges for usage. we have usage charges and standing charges. If you have a smart meter thatn can measure import and export then you get paid for what you export it is about half what you pay to export, so you want to try to nto export. But because there are a lot a non smart meters. in those cases they give you a deeped export based ont he soze of your inverter.. So today I've generated 11Kwh,  I've exported a lot of that 6.5kWh but because I am deemed export it doesn't matter how much I export I get paid the same. I've only consumed 7kWh today but I did import 2.5kWh. The trick is matching the appliances and the Sun.

I could get a battery and export less, but its about a 15 year payback so not much point.
I only have a 2.4kWh system but if I could get it to maybe 4kWh and a battery. That coupled with a bit of wind would really reduce the amount of Co2 generated.

I would have thought lots of the US woul have a summer peak where AC is the major driver and Solar and AC must be a great mix really. In Ireland our Energy use is in the winter, noone has AC at home at all.

I would support nuclear for baseload, but I can't see it happen in Ireland for a while. Chernobyl is still in the popular Psyche here , due in no small part to a great charity that brought children from Belarus to Cork for holidays.

Author: joshuastover
Content:
Not totally sure how the meter is setup. I didn't dive into it. Unfortunately there are other energy providers, but the terms of the city's contracts make it difficult for people on the city's energy plan to leave and go with a new plan (that area of the state is fairly corrupt ğŸ˜•) In Texas there are pretty good incentives for solar. 

As far as energy usage goes, it really depends what part of the country you're in is. State's in the Sun Belt (like Texas) use a lot more energy during the Summer (our energy use doubles,) but in the Rust belt I suppose there's more energy demand in the Winter. You a good chunk of the US where you need AC during the Summer, and need quite a bit of energy for heat during the Winter. Then you have California, who lives in a constant state of 70 Degrees F and Sunny ğŸ¤£ 

Solar is really good in the South. You're seeing more and more homes install solar panels on their roofs, particularly in Texas and Florida. I'm not too privy to the Solar incentives to other states, but if my knowledge serves me well, Texas and Florida have some really good incentives for it.

Content: If that is a suicide cable Brian, be careful.  Funny story, I plugged a din-rail power supply to a network rack at the Arlington GM plant on the production line. It was the only avaliable 120v outlet I could find. I was setting up some banner wireless radios and needed 24v. The issue was who ever trimmed the wires at the power supply terminal, trimmed too much, so there were a few millimeters of copper that were exposed. While I was working, I accidently kicked the power supply over, causing the suicide cable to short, causing the network cabinet to throw a breaker, turning off the whole production line. My friends don't even call me white, they tell me I'm more pasty than white. At that moment, when everyone's head turned to me as the guy that shut the whole line down, I turned transparent.

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
I would recommend.
Do the Free IoT course https://www.iiot.university/
Do the Inductive Automation Ignition university  https://inductiveuniversity.com/
And read all of the stuff on 
here  https://learn.umh.app/ , 
here https://www.hivemq.com/blog/

If your not a reader,
Follow Kudzai Manditereza on Linkedin and watch his videos on youtube if you are already not
Follow 4.0Solutions on LinkedIn and wat the videos on youtube 

Learn Python, or at least how to code with Python Via ChatGPT. There are a lot of courses online
Learn a bit about containers, Docker and portainer.

Download the Ming Stack - Mosquitto, Influx, Node Red, and Grafana, and replace Influx with timescale if you want to be cool.

If you have a PLC handy, maybe , maybe simulate a machine. and build some Logic in node red, convert the PLC tags into MQTT topics, Store data in Timescale, and graph it in Grafana.

If you don't have a PLC, just write a python script to simulate a machine with a modbus 

If you don't know how, as Chat GPT to guide you through
- Write a Python script that counts from 1 to 100 and then resets and stored that values in a modbus register
    (or one that writes the CPU usage, Ram Usage and processor temp to modbus registers)
- Write a node-Red Flow to read the value from modbus and publish it to a MQTT broker
- Write a Node Red Flow to subscribe to that topic and store the value in a Database.
- Create a Grafana screen that monitors the Value in the Data base.

Then ask Chat GPT how to install the Mind Stack in a docker container and go again.

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
Zach, 
I fully agree that Elon Musk is the Entrepreneur of probably the Century . Certainly of our time, hands down, 
But there are two things, 

I look at what he claims on timelines, and compare it to what that reality is, so I have a trust issue with any of the other claims too.
And I don't think it was just overly optimistic, I think it is lying but I don't know. maybe he did have a Saudi Investor to take Tesla Private.

And then he was also very lucky. He built a manufacturing company, and didn't outsource, and it paid off, but it was really close to not paying off, so did . He was able to get insane amounts of capital, in what it might be claimed as lets say questionable ways. But when I say lucky I fully acknowledge that there ae only a small cohort of people who could put themselves into the position to take advantage of those lucky breaks. And Kudos to him, honestly

But I think any discussion ultimately comes down to.
Tesla is probably the most advanced manufacturing company in the world,( I don't have numbers so don't know)

Author: ted.garrison
Content: Is a party only allowed to put up 3 names? or is that just all FF & FG had that wished to run?

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
A party puts up as many as they want, but you need to get 20% +1vote to be elected, so if you have too many candidates you can spread your vote too thin and they all get eliminated. so you normally run the number of candidates you think you can get +1

For Context the current government is FF,FG and Greens , Fianna Fail( Soldiers of Destiny) and Fianna Gael( Soldiers of Ireland) are the two sides of the Irish Civil war, both very centrist( FG a bit more to the right), and one of they has lead every government since the foundation of the state,

for FF Michael Martin is a former Taoiseach( PM), FF party Leader, has been elected for the past 40 years or so, 
Seamus McGrath is a  local councillor but he got the highest first preference votes of any councillor in Ireland in the last local elections, and his Brother is a former finance minister and  current European commissioner,
Margret Kenneally - she is really mopping up votes, if she can get people from here area to vote for her and give then their no 2 to Seamus McGrath when whe is eliminated he might get across the line.

Donncagh O'Laoighaire , is a sitting TD for Sinm Finn, the main opposition party, they are having some scandals at the moment, so a year ago  they would have been hoping to pull Michelly Cowhey Shahid across the line with her, but it might be a bit too far,

FG, their deputy leader is retiring, so there is a bit of a gap they have two popular councillors and Jerry Buttimer a former TD and current Senator (our senate is not directly elected). I think they will get 1 seat, but it could be any of the three, and it might two of them left after a couple round and whoever has the nose ahead when the other gets eliminated , will be elected.

the fifth seat will be a battle royal, between a second SF and FG seat and I would say Mick Finn( a popular local socialist), and depend very much on Transfers,

If you get les than a certain vote, you don't get a deposit back.

Author: ted.garrison
Content: Do folks in Ireland move their vote between parties more?  I'd assume so, since you're using Ranked Choice which allows for more fine-tuning than the crap system we have over here..

Author: ted.garrison
Content: also with as many parties, I'm guessing each party is more "focused", whereas over here, we basically have the Nazis, and everything left of the Nazis. (which is still not really leftish compared to many European countries)

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
Yes but in often unexpected ways.
The Irish parties are very huddled around the centre( even the centre left support a low corporation tax)

 In 1919 Ireland was partitioned in to Northern Ireland and the rest.
So at the end of the war of Independence, we signed a Treaty with the UK giving the remainder independence, and the main Political Party in the State was sin Fein, however it split between the supporters of the treaty and those who wanted to keep fighting for Norther Ireland.
that split lead to a civil war and the two sides became Fianna Fail( anti Treaty) and Fine Gael( pro Treaty). And Until 5 years ago one of those parties formed the govt.
normally FF with majority and Fina Gael ,the more right wing party with the support of Labour. We had a 2 and a half party system.

so given there was a civil war, very few votes were transferred between FF and FG.

in the 90's smaller parties and independents started to gain traction so not FF and FG get about 40% of the vote, and 5 years ago went into coalition , with the greens.

So I expect there to be a lot of transfers between those two. Which would have been madness in my grandparents generation

sometimes people want to vote against the status quo and there votes might go from a very right wing to a very left wing party.
there are also a cluster of centre smaller  left parties( Social democrats, Labour, even the Greens) who will transfer a lot between each other, but not as many will transfer to Sinn Fein, through very similar positioning wise.

Sinn Fein don't trace back to the original Sin Fein , but really come from Northern Ireland where they were the political wing of the IRA.  with the Good Friday Agreement, they have reformed and become very popular as an alternative left party. they have taken a lot of traditional Labour support, and had a huge vote in the last election, but not enough to form a government despite being the largest party.

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
And of course parochialism and local politics can play a huge role.
Many people will vote for someone from their area over Policy, especially if you think that person might become a Minister in the next government.
so a more right wing candidate can transfer a lot of votes to a left wing candidate becuase they come from the same area.

Especially if the constituency has two counties.

imagine a 6 seater in the US where 6 congress people from North and South Dakota will be elected. I might vote for  two South Dakota candidates first even though they are Republican and Democrat

Author: sparkylarks
Content:
you also have places like South Kerry where the Healy-Rae's are a political dynasty with out a Party.
out of three seats two are independent brothers Michael and Danny won two of the seats, and they have three of the next generation serving as councillors.

And that would be very much a Vote against Dublin and central government,

People should have a vote, and feel like using it matters.

To me the biggest issue with first past the post, is 
- you often end up voting against the party you dislike more.
- you end up voting strategically to achieve that.

that can lead to strategic voting and people don't get to vote for the person they actually want.

with ranked choice it gives smaller parties a chance, Their supporters can vote for them, and show that they support them, but still end up with a usefull vote.
that can signal to other voters that actually there is more support here for Party X I might get involved.

but the multi seat to me is really great for participations.

Look at Texas and California, both about 60/40 when you look at votes cast. but 2 senators from the same party in each.
Imagine running both Senate seats at the same time and the top two get in.
and a popular third part might even have a chance to get sneak a seat in.

Author: r.pop
Content:
All recruiting companies are not created equal. In my experience, I haven't had any issues being recruited by one or using one to find people. Generally though, I have noticed they tend to inflate salaries as it earns them a higher commission. Recruiters are usually hired by a company to find a specific skillset, and are usually paid 20% of the base salary. So the higher the salary, the higher the commission. 

This can work great for the candidate though, since they will be pushing to get you more salary. Depending on the contract with the hiring company, there is usually a clause that makes that fee refundable or waives it on the next hire if the candidate is not up to par or let go within the first 1-6 months (again depending on contract).

Content: You need a diverse skillset and you're probably not going to be able to find someone with all of them, at least not in someone you can afford. I work with a team of 6 people. I'm an architect and general jack-of-all-trades, we also have someone who's really good at the Tulip platoform, one that's good with PLCs, one that's good with automation (both robots and inspection), one that's pretty technical but a whiz at SQL databases, and a Program Manager.

Author: r.pop
Content:
I typically pull from 1 of 2 talent pools, bonus if I can get both in the same engineer right off the bat. 

Pool 1 (OT) = Controls/Automation Engineers. Someone that knows how the things in a factory work. Robots, PLCs, OPCUA, Sensors, etc. 

Pool 2 (IT) = Cloud Solution Architects and Software Developers. Someone that understands how to write software (not PLC programming) and has a strong knowledge of structured programming and databases. Or someone with a background in cloud dev ops. 

I then cross train these people on the area theyâ€™re lacking in. So if I hire a OT person, the first thing theyâ€™re going to do is go through AWS Solution Architects Associate certification. And if I hire an IT person the first thing theyâ€™re going to do is get Ignition certification.

Author: _dyland
Content:
If you want a Masters degree for personal reasons, and you don't have to take on debt then there are a lot of upsides to it. If you need to take on debt, then the equation becomes harder to justify in my book... But the only one who can answer that for you is you.

If the goal is to become a better problem solver though, I really don't think a masters degree will get you there. 

I personally hire engineers with degrees when I want someone who can think inside the box. Someone with the discipline to complete documentation or someone who I need to read and understand  industry standards.

When I am hiring someone who needs to think outside the box that degree is either meaningless or even a slight detriment in a tie breaker. Real problem solving abilities are not learned in a classroom, they are learned through real life experience, failures, triumphs, and long nights struggling to find a viable solution. 

Though, to touch on the reasons for not being able to self learn.

If you don't trust your judgement, a degree won't give you the confidence you need to overcome this. This will be a much larger hurdle than any lack of problem solving or technical abilities. 

If you don't have time to watch some videos, read some books, and play with the tools on your own time - what makes you think you will have time for a masters program?

Basically, if you lack the discipline to learn on your own - a degree won't do much of anything for you...  

I don't know of any degree that will teach you discipline or true problem solving skills that will translate to the real world. 

That said, I have worked with, for, and even hired people with technical PHDs, BFAs, Associates, High School diplomas, and almost everything in between. Some of them felt it was worth it and others didn't.

Author: _dyland
Content: For reference, I have an associates degree. In my first year of my career I worked for a machine builder - electrical and mechanical assembly, service calls, machine installs, the panel shop, and even some time spent in AutoCAD with the engineers. In my second year, I started to get into electrical engineering for an electrical contractor and thateas me into controls and PLC programming in my 3rd year. In my 5th year I was responsible for entire automation projects with hundreds of IO points and dozens of motors. This 5th year lined up with some friends who got their Masters 1st year in the industry.

Author: _dyland
Content: Back to you though... Honestly, I would work on gaining the discipline to self learn by forcing yourself to self learn. There are guided courses that are free on EdX ( https://www.edx.org/ ). Almost everything you could ever learn is on YouTube. There are paid courses on sites like udemy, Coursera, Skillshare, and LinkedIn Learning as well.

Author: _dyland
Content: Sorry if it's not what you want to hear but I would work on what makes you feel like you can't self learn - and then learn in a way that makes sense to you.

Author: _dyland
Content:
But as I said before. Some people found their degrees with the corresponding debt and time spent to be worth it. Others didn't. 

Only you can make that decision for yourself.

I think the technical term was "Robotic Automated Systems Technology" or something like that. It was like 90 something credits in 5 semesters. We started with 22 in our class and I think 16 graduated. 

It was basically a factory that turned out service techs for the big local packaging Machine Builders... We started with "What is an atom" that went into electrical theory, digital electronics, motors and drives, PLCs pneumatics, CAD, Machining, and Fanuc robots. Capstone was groups of 4 designing and building robotic cells with a couple Robots each. 

All that, and the most important thing they taught was troubleshooting. One example is, when doing the capstone, they would replace a fuse with a bad one so that when we got there in the morning the things that worked yesterday didn't work today. When we asked for a manual they would purposely give us the wrong one or make us look it up online. 

As for resources, everyone learns differently, for me most of what I know came from client requests or generally solving problems in the moment. When I want to learn more about stuff outside of that I try to spin up what I can in a home lab and get my hands dirty. 

For me, nothing teaches me better than just doing it. 

And for better and worse, I spent a lot of my career at a fledgling integrator where I had no choice but to figure it out on the fly.

Author: tyler092335
Content: Thanks for detailing that out! It helps knowing someone else has a similar path to me ha. I didn't get much into robotics but we also did a capstone project after each semester where they bugged what we had build. Right now at my company we are deploying the infrastructure of a Digital transformation (Mqtt broker, Ignition, and dataops with cloud AI). Im learning a tone and it is fun. My problem is just like any end user at a manufacturing plant, I wear multiple hats. Finding time to really focus and learn at a quicker pace can be challenging. I think in the future I might switch to a integration job where I can see multiple things to get my hands 'dirty' with more technologies.
